<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">Shaped for Sharp<span class="AddHand-author">en</span>ing scythes and Carpenters Tools, they are of different figures and some of them of a very fine grit<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Point at each extremity of the bay is a Red freestone and from fifty to sixty feet high<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  You mount the River for two leagues; at Some distance from the enterance it dividees into three branches the middlemost of which is the Shortest and leads you to a Lake of perhaps three legues in circumference the water of which is exceedingly black and abounds with Sturgeon<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>he land is extremely high all Round it and to wards the Southwestern extremity a Small band of Indians have their garden grounds on an elevation of at least Sixty feet above the level of the lake, in as Rich a Soil as I ever Saw<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The lake narrows away to the westward where you enter a little Serpentine River which is mounted with much difficulty<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[Y]</span>ou then enter a little marshy lake of about a mile long at the farther end of which you have to draw your Canoe through the mud at the Risk of having the men mired up to their necks: here you have to discharge and carry every thing through the mire for better than a mile; the ground then Rises and you have a fine Sandy path to the Other end of the Portage<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Near this Portage the Indians have often found pieces of Virgin Copper of the purest kind<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[31]</span></p>

